<body>
    <h1>Introduction to REST</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoREST-WhatisREST(RepresentationalStateTransf=
er)?">What is REST (Representational State Transfer)?</h3>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" heigh=
t=3D"117" src=3D"11a0e998bc0b0cf3a6c71c49a5c41ab9436518d3a4ad1c922c84dcf59f=
9b418c" data-image-src=3D"/download/attachments/1203279299/image2021-11-22_=
13-21-35.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationDate=3D1663571073880&amp;api=3Dv2"=
 data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"1203279301"=
 data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment=
" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image2021-11-22_13-21-35.png" data-=
base-url=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au" data-linked-resource-con=
tent-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-container-id=3D"1203279299" da=
ta-linked-resource-container-version=3D"2" alt=3D"" width=3D"321"></span></=
p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">REST (REpresentational State Trans=
fer) is<span>&nbsp;</span></span><em>an architectural style</em><span style=
=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);"><span>&nbsp;</span>for designing networked appli=
cations. The term was coined by Roy Fielding in 2000 in his now-famous PhD =
dissertation<span>&nbsp;</span></span><a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"ht=
tp://www.ics.uci.edu/~fielding/pubs/dissertation/rest_arch_style.htm" style=
=3D"text-decoration: none;" rel=3D"nofollow">Architectural Styles and the D=
esign of Network-based Software Architectures</a><span style=3D"color: rgb(=
23,43,77);">. The REST architectural style has been used to guide the desig=
n and development of the architecture for the modern Web and thus is based =
on HTTP concepts.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">The 3 core concepts in REST are: r=
esources, methods (verbs) and response codes.</span></p>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoREST-WhatisaRESTfulAPI?">What is a RESTful API?</h3=
>
<p>Conforming to the REST constraints is generally referred to as being =E2=
=80=9CRESTful=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p>Complying with these constraints, and thus conforming to the REST archit=
ectural style enables any kind of distributed hypermedia system to have des=
irable emergent properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, m=
odifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.</p>
<p>The key components of REST are: resources, actions and response codes. R=
esources are used to encapsulate the information to be processed and are re=
presented in the form of URIs (eg. <a href=3D"http://api.example.com/custom=
ers" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">http://api.example.com/custom=
ers</a>). Actions are represented as HTTP methods (verbs) which include GET=
, PUT, POST, DELETE and are used to indicate the nature of processing requi=
red. Response codes indicate whether processing was successful or not; typi=
cal response codes are 200 (Ok), 400 (Bad Request), 404 (Not Found), 500 (I=
nternal Server Error).</p>
<p>Key points for successfully offering a RESTful API are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Use HTTP Verbs as intended in RFC7231</li>
<li>Provide sensible resource names</li>
<li>Use HTTP response codes to indicate status</li>
<li>Create resources at the right level of granularity</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"IntroductiontoREST-WhatisaResource?">What is a Resource?</h3>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" heigh=
t=3D"133" src=3D"24756d318d98f70ceb0e2e1668ca07ed0bead77c05b1feb770929d9249=
22d404" data-image-src=3D"/download/attachments/1203279299/image2021-11-22_=
13-22-21.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationDate=3D1663571073803&amp;api=3Dv2"=
 data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"1203279300"=
 data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment=
" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image2021-11-22_13-22-21.png" data-=
base-url=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au" data-linked-resource-con=
tent-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-container-id=3D"1203279299" da=
ta-linked-resource-container-version=3D"2" alt=3D"" width=3D"333"></span></=
p>
<p>Resources form the nucleus of any REST API design.<span>&nbsp;</span><sp=
an style=3D"color: rgb(51,51,51);" lang=3D"EN">Any information that can be =
named can be a resource: a document or image, a temporal service (e.g. "tod=
ay's weather in Los Angeles"), a collection of other resources, a non-virtu=
al object (e.g. a person), and so on.&nbsp;</span>It is very important to s=
elect the right resources and model the resources at the right granularity =
while designing the REST API so that the API consumers get the desired func=
tionality from the API's.</p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,51,51);" lang=3D"EN">The starting point in =
selection of resources is to analyse your business domain and extract the n=
ouns that are relevant to your business needs. More importantly, focus shou=
ld be given to the needs of API consumers and how to make the API relevant =
and useful from the perspective of API consumer interactions. Once the noun=
s (resources) have been identified, then the interactions with the API can =
be modelled as HTTP verbs against these nouns. When they don't map nicely, =
we could approximate. For example, we can easily use the =E2=80=9Cnouns in =
the domain=E2=80=9D approach and identify low level resources such as Post,=
 Tag, Comment, etc. in a blogging domain. Similarly, we can identify the no=
uns Customer, Address, Account, Teller, etc. as resources in a banking doma=
in.</span></p>
<p><strong>Further reading on what is a resource:</strong> <a href=3D"https=
://www.thoughtworks.com/insights/blog/rest-api-design-resource-modeling" st=
yle=3D"" rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external-link"><span style=3D"color: rgb=
(51,102,255);">https://www.thoughtworks.com/insights/blog/rest-api-design-r=
esource-modeling</span></a></p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
